File Commands 

1. Is : Directory listing 
2. Is -al : Formatted listing with hidden files 
3. Is -It : Sorting the Formatted listing by time modification 
4. cd dir : Change directory to dir 
5. cd : Change to home directory 
6. pwd : Show current working directory 
7. mkdir dir : Creating a directory dir 
8. cat >file : Places the standard input into the file 
9. more file : Output the contents of the file 
10. head file : Output the first 10 lines of the file 
11. tail file : Output the last 10 lines of the file 
12. tail -f file : Output the contents of file as it grows,starting with the last 10 lines 
13. touch file : Create or update file 
14. rm file : Deleting the file 
15. rm -r dir : Deleting the directory 
16. rm -f file : Force to remove the file 
17. rm -rf dir : Force to remove the directory dir 
18. cp filel file2 : Copy the contents of filel to file2 
19. cp-r dirl dir2 : Copy dirl to dir2;create dir2 if not present

Process management 
1. ps : To display the currently working processes 
2. top : Display all running process 
3. kill pid : Kill the process with given pid 
4. killall : proc Kill all the process named proc 
5. pkill pattern : Will kill all processes matching the pattern 
6. bg : List stopped or background jobs,resume a stopped job in the background 
7. fg : Brings the most recent job to foreground 
8. fg n : Brings job n to the foreground 

System Info 
1. date : Show the current date and time 
2. cal : Show this month's calender 
3. uptime : Show current uptime 
4. w : Display who is on line 
5. whoami : Who you are logged in as 
6. finger user Display information about user 
7. uname -a : Show kernel information 
8. cat/proc/cpuinfo : Cpu information 
9. cat proc/meminfo : Memory information 
10. man : command Show the manual for command 
11. df : Show the disk usage 
12. du : Show directory space usage 
13. free : Show memory and swap usage 
14. whereis app : Show possible locations of app 
15. which app : Show which applications will be run by default

Compression 
1. tar cf file.tar file : Create tar named file.tar containing file 
2. tar xf file.tar : Extract the files from file.tar 
3. tar czf file.tar.gz files : Create a tar with Gzip compression 
4. tar xzf file.tar.gz : Extract a tar using Gzip 
5. tar cif file.tar.bz2 : Create tar with Bzip2 compression 
6. tar xjf file.tar.bz2 : Extract a tar using Bzip2 
7. gzip file : Compresses file and renames it to file.gz 
8. gzip -d file.gz : Decompresses file.gz back to file 

Network 
1. ping host : Ping host and output results 
2. whois domain : Get whois information for domains 
3. dig domain : Get DNS information for domain 
4. dig -x host : Reverse lookup host 
5. wget file : Download file 
6. wget -c file : Continue a stopped download

Shortcuts 
1. ctrl+c : Halts the current command 
2. ctrl+z : Stops the current command, resume with fg in the foreground or bg in the background 
3. ctrl+d : Logout the current session, similar to exit 
4. ctrl+w : Erases one word in the current line 
5. ctrl+u : Erases the whole line 
6. ctrl+r : Type to bring up a recent command 
7.!! : Repeats the last command 
8. exit : Logout the current session

Disk Usage Commands:
1. df [options] : Displays disk space usage for mounted file systems.
  a. -h : Human-readable format (KB, MB, GB).
  b. -T : Displays the file system type.
  c. -a : Includes pseudo, duplicate, and inaccessible file systems.
  d. -l : Limits output to local file systems only.
  e. -t [type] : Displays file systems of the specified type.
  f. -x [type] : Excludes file systems of the specified type.
2. df -h : Displays disk usage in a human-readable format (KB, MB, GB).
3. df -T : Shows the type of the file system.
4. df -a : Includes pseudo, duplicate, and inaccessible file systems.
5. df -l : Limits output to local file systems only.
6. df -t ext4 : Shows file systems of the specified type (ext4).
7. df -x tmpfs : Excludes file systems of the specified type (tmpfs).

Memory Usage Commands:
1. free [options] : Displays memory usage (free, used, swap, buffer).
  a. -m : Displays memory in megabytes.
  b. -g : Displays memory in gigabytes.
  c. -h : Human-readable format (auto-adjusting units).
  d. -b : Displays memory in bytes.
  e. -t : Shows total memory and swap space.
  f. -s [seconds] : Repeats the memory usage output every specified number of
seconds.
2. free -m : Displays memory in megabytes.
3. free -g : Displays memory in gigabytes.
4. free -h : Displays memory in a human-readable format.
5. free -b : Displays memory in bytes.
6. free -t : Shows total memory and swap space.
7. free -s [seconds] : Repeats the memory usage output every specified number of
seconds.

CPU and Process Information Commands:
1. nproc [options] : Displays the number of processing units (CPUs/cores).
a. --all : Displays the total number of processing units available.
b. --core : Displays the number of cores.
c. --help : Displays help information.
2. nproc --all : Displays the total number of processing units available.
3. nproc --core : Displays the number of cores.
4. nproc --help : Displays help information.

Process Monitoring Commands:
1. top [options] : Displays real-time system resource usage, including processes and
memory.
  a. -d [seconds] : Updates the display every specified number of seconds.
  b. -n [iterations] : Specifies the number of updates to run.
  c. -u [user] : Displays processes for a specific user.
  d. -p [pid] : Displays processes with the specified PID.
  e. -b : Runs in batch mode (suitable for output redirection).
  f. -i : Ignores idle and zombie processes.
2. top -d [seconds] : Updates the display every specified number of seconds.
3. top -n [iterations] : Specifies the number of updates to run.
4. top -u [user] : Displays processes for a specific user.
5. top -p [pid] : Displays processes with the specified PID.
6. top -b : Runs in batch mode (suitable for output redirection).
7. top -i : Ignores idle and zombie processes.

Process Status Commands:
1. ps [options] : Displays information about active processes.
  a. a : Shows processes associated with a terminal.
  b. u : Displays processes in a user-oriented format.
  c. x : Displays processes without a controlling terminal.
  d. -e : Displays all processes.
  e. -f : Shows full format information, including PPID.
2. ps a : Shows processes associated with a terminal.
3. ps u : Displays processes in a user-oriented format.
4. ps x : Displays processes without a controlling terminal.
5. ps -e : Displays all processes.
6. ps -f : Shows full format information, including PPID.

Text Search and Manipulation Commands:
1. grep [options] pattern [file...] : Searches for a pattern in files.
  a. -i : Performs a case-insensitive search.
  b. -r : Recursively searches files in a directory.
  c. -v : Inverts the match, showing lines that do not match the pattern.
  d. -l : Displays only filenames that contain the pattern.
  e. -n : Shows line numbers for matches.
  f. -c : Shows the count of matching lines.
2. grep -i "pattern" file.txt : Performs a case-insensitive search.
3. grep -r "pattern" /path/to/dir/ : Recursively searches files in a directory.
4. grep -v "pattern" file.txt : Inverts the match, showing lines that do not match the
pattern.
5. grep -l "pattern" * : Displays only filenames that contain the pattern.
6. grep -n "pattern" file.txt : Shows line numbers for matches.
7. grep -c "pattern" file.txt : Shows the count of matching lines.

Text Processing Commands:
1. awk [options] '{print $1}' [file...] : Processes and manipulates text data by fields.
  a. -F [separator] : Defines a custom field separator.
  b. NR : Prints the current line number.
  c. $1, $2, etc. : Refers to specific fields in the input data.
  d. print : Outputs text or data to the screen.
2. awk -F, '{print $1}' file.csv : Specifies a custom field delimiter (comma for CSV).
3. awk '{print NR, $0}' file.txt : Prints the line number and entire line.
4. awk '{print $1, $3}' file.txt : Prints the first and third columns.

Stream Editing Commands:
1. sed [options] 's/old/new/g' [file...] : Stream editor for text substitution.
  a. -i : Modifies the file in place.
  b. -e : Allows multiple editing commands.
  c. /pattern/d : Deletes lines matching the pattern.
  d. -n : Suppresses automatic printing (use p to print).
2. sed -i 's/old/new/g' file.txt : Modifies the file in place.
3. sed 's/old/new/1' file.txt : Replaces the first occurrence of "old" with "new".
4. sed -e 's/old/new/g' -e 's/test/example/g' file.txt : Uses multiple expressions
(commands).
5. sed '/pattern/d' file.txt : Deletes lines matching the pattern.
6. sed -n '/pattern/p' file.txt : Prints lines matching the pattern.

Text Cutting Commands:
1. cut [options] [file...] : Extracts sections from text input (fields, characters).
  a. -d [delimiter] : Specifies the delimiter (e.g., comma, space).
  b. -f [fields] : Specifies which fields to extract.
  c. -c [range] : Specifies which characters to extract.
2. cut -d ":" -f 1 file.txt : Cuts the first field separated by a colon.
3. cut -f 1,3 file.txt : Cuts fields 1 and 3.
4. cut -c 1-5 file.txt : Cuts characters from position 1 to 5.

Character Translation Commands:
1. tr [options] [set1] [set2] : Translates or deletes characters from a stream.
  a. -d : Deletes characters in the first set.
  b. -s : Squeezes repeated characters.
2. tr 'a-z' 'A-Z' : Converts lowercase characters to uppercase.
3. tr -d '[:space:]' : Deletes whitespace characters.
4. tr -s ' ' ' ' : Squeezes multiple spaces into a single space.

File Download and Fetching Commands:
1. curl [options] [URL] : Fetches data from a URL or sends data to a URL.
  a. -O : Downloads the file from the URL.
  b. -X [method] : Specifies the request method (e.g., GET, POST).
  c. -I : Fetches the HTTP headers only.
  d. -d [data] : Sends data with the request (for POST).
  e. -L : Follows redirects.
2. curl -O [URL] : Downloads a file from the URL.
3. curl -X GET [URL] : Performs a GET request to fetch data from the URL.
4. wget [options] [URL] : Downloads files from the web.
5. wget -q [URL] : Downloads a file quietly without output.

File Searching Commands:
1. find [directory] [options] : Searches for files in a directory hierarchy.
  a. -name [pattern] : Searches for files matching a name pattern.
  b. -type [type] : Searches for files of a specific type (e.g., file, directory).
  c. -exec [command] {} \; : Executes a command on the found files.
  d. -size [size] : Searches for files of a specific size.
2. find /home -name "*.txt" : Finds all text files in the /home directory.
3. find / -type f -size +100M : Finds files larger than 100MB.
4. find /path/to/dir -name "*.log" -exec rm {} \; : Finds and deletes log files.

Signal Handling Commands:
1. trap [command] [signal] : Specifies a command to execute when receiving a signal.
  a. SIGINT : Interrupt signal (Ctrl+C).
  b. SIGTERM : Termination signal.
2. trap 'echo "Caught signal!"' SIGINT : Prints a message when Ctrl+C (SIGINT) is
pressed.
